{"title_page": "Plantago ovata", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Plantago ovata form.jpg\n|genus = Plantago\n|species = ovata\n|authority = [[Forssk.]]\n|synonyms =\n  {{Specieslist\n  |Plantago brunnea|Morris\n  |Plantago fastigiata|Morris\n  |Plantago gooddingii|A.Nels. & Kennedy\n  |Plantago insularis|Eastw.\n  |Plantago minima|A.Cunningham\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''''Plantago ovata''''', known by many [[common name]]s including '''blond plantain''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web |title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |accessdate=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> '''desert Indianwheat''',<ref>{{citation |url=http://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=PLOV |title=USDA PLANTS |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref> '''blond psyllium''',<ref name=GRIN>{{citation |url=https://npgsweb.ars-grin.gov/gringlobal/taxonomydetail.aspx?id=28790 |title=USDA GRIN Taxonomy |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref> and '''ispaghul''',<ref name=GRIN/> is a [[medicinal plant]] native to [[Western Asia|Western]] and [[Southern Asia]]. The plant can be found growing wild in the southwestern United State and is native.\n\nIt is a common source of [[psyllium]], a type of [[dietary fiber]].<ref>[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/natural/866.html Medlineplus. Blond psyllium (a.k.a. ''Plantago ovata'')]. Effectiveness, interactions with medications, etc.</ref> Psyllium seed husks are indigestible and are a source of soluble fiber which may be fermented into [[butyric acid|butyrate]]&nbsp;\u2013 a [[pharmacologically active]] [[short-chain fatty acid]]&nbsp;\u2013 by [[Butyric acid#Biosynthesis|butyrate-producing bacteria]].<ref name=\"psillium husk fermentation - butyrate\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fern\u00e1ndez-Ba\u00f1ares F, Hinojosa J, S\u00e1nchez-Lombra\u00f1a JL, Navarro E, Mart\u00ednez-Salmer\u00f3n JF, Garc\u00eda-Pug\u00e9s A, Gonz\u00e1lez-Huix F, Riera J, Gonz\u00e1lez-Lara V, Dom\u00ednguez-Abascal F, Gin\u00e9 JJ, Moles J, Gomoll\u00f3n F, Gassull MA | title = Randomized clinical trial of ''Plantago ovata'' seeds (dietary fiber) as compared with mesalamine in maintaining remission in ulcerative colitis. Spanish Group for the Study of Crohn's Disease and Ulcerative Colitis (GETECCU) | journal = Am. J. Gastroenterol. | volume = 94 | issue = 2 | pages = 427\u201333 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10022641 | doi=10.1016/s0002-9270(98)00753-9}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Psyllium]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Plantago+ovata Plants For A Future: ''Plantago ovata'']\n*[http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_JM_treatment.pl?5625,5626,5636 Jepson Manual Treatment]\n*[http://calphotos.berkeley.edu/cgi/img_query?query_src=photos_index&where-taxon=Plantago+ovata Photo gallery]\n\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q311228}}\n\n[[Category:Plantago|ovata]]\n[[Category:Flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Flora of the United States]]\n[[Category:Flora of North Africa]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Peter Forssk\u00e5l]]\n\n\n{{Lamiales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Plantago ovata form.jpg\n|genus = Plantago\n|species = ovata\n|authority = [[Forssk.]]\n|synonyms =\n  {{Specieslist\n  |Plantago brunnea|Morris\n  |Plantago fastigiata|Morris\n  |Plantago gooddingii|A.Nels. & Kennedy\n  |Plantago insularis|Eastw.\n  |Plantago minima|A.Cunningham\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''''Plantago ovata''''', known by many [[common name]]s including '''blond plantain''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web |title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |accessdate=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> '''desert Indianwheat''',<ref>{{citation |url=http://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=PLOV |title=USDA PLANTS |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref> '''blond psyllium''',<ref name=GRIN>{{citation |url=https://npgsweb.ars-grin.gov/gringlobal/taxonomydetail.aspx?id=28790 |title=USDA GRIN Taxonomy |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref> and '''ispaghul''',<ref name=GRIN/> is a [[medicinal plant]] native to [[Western Asia|Western]] and [[Southern Asia]]. The plant can be found growing wild in the southwestern United State and is native.|title=Plantago ovata Forssk |work=madrean.org |date=n.d. |accessdate=April 26, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIt is a common source of [[psyllium]], a type of [[dietary fiber]].<ref>[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/natural/866.html Medlineplus. Blond psyllium (a.k.a. ''Plantago ovata'')]. Effectiveness, interactions with medications, etc.</ref> Psyllium seed husks are indigestible and are a source of soluble fiber which may be fermented into [[butyric acid|butyrate]]&nbsp;\u2013 a [[pharmacologically active]] [[short-chain fatty acid]]&nbsp;\u2013 by [[Butyric acid#Biosynthesis|butyrate-producing bacteria]].<ref name=\"psillium husk fermentation - butyrate\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fern\u00e1ndez-Ba\u00f1ares F, Hinojosa J, S\u00e1nchez-Lombra\u00f1a JL, Navarro E, Mart\u00ednez-Salmer\u00f3n JF, Garc\u00eda-Pug\u00e9s A, Gonz\u00e1lez-Huix F, Riera J, Gonz\u00e1lez-Lara V, Dom\u00ednguez-Abascal F, Gin\u00e9 JJ, Moles J, Gomoll\u00f3n F, Gassull MA | title = Randomized clinical trial of ''Plantago ovata'' seeds (dietary fiber) as compared with mesalamine in maintaining remission in ulcerative colitis. Spanish Group for the Study of Crohn's Disease and Ulcerative Colitis (GETECCU) | journal = Am. J. Gastroenterol. | volume = 94 | issue = 2 | pages = 427\u201333 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10022641 | doi=10.1016/s0002-9270(98)00753-9}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Psyllium]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n